me\">instAddMonoidWithOne</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">n</span> : <a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Nat\">ℕ</a>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"impl_arg\"><span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">[<span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./Init/Data/NeZero.html#NeZero\">NeZero</a> <span class=\"fn\">n</span></span>]</span></span>\n</span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./Mathlib/Data/Nat/Cast/Defs.html#AddMonoidWithOne\">AddMonoidWithOne</a> <span class=\"fn\">(<a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Fin\">Fin</a> <span class=\"fn\">n</span>)</span></span></div></div>","info":{"doc":"This is not a global instance, but can introduced locally using `open Fin.NatCast in ...`.\n\nThis is not an instance because the `binop%` elaborator assumes that\nthere are no non-trivial coercion loops,\nbut this instance would introduce a coercion from `Nat` to `Fin n` and back.\nNon-trivial loops lead to undesirable and counterintuitive elaboration behavior.\n\nFor example, for `x : Fin k` and `n : Nat`,\nit causes `x < n` to be elaborated as `x < ↑n` rather than `↑x < n`,\nsilently introducing wraparound arithmetic.\n","docLink":"./Mathlib/Algebra/Group/Fin/Basic.html#Fin.instAddMonoidWithOne","kind":"def","line":42,"name":"Fin.instAddMonoidWithOne","sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/0f1dd7505c3d08b5feb82300ccc73179a457bf51/Mathlib/Algebra/Group/Fin/Basic.lean#L42-L59"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">instance</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./Mathlib/Algebra/Group/Fin/Basic.html#Fin.addCommMonoid\"><span class=\"name\">Fin</span>.<span class=\"name\">addCommMonoid</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">n</span> : <a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Nat\">ℕ</a>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"impl_arg\"><span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">[<span c